e key insight here is that each unique positive number in the array will require a separate operation to be reduced to zero. Therefore, the number of operations needed is equal to the number of unique positive numbers in the array.\n\nHere's the step-by-step approach:\n\n1. Convert the list `nums` to a set to eliminate duplicates.\n2. Remove the zero from the set if it exists, as zeros do not require any operations.\n3. The size of the resulting set will be the number of operations needed.\n\nLet's implement this in the provided format:\n\n```python\nfrom typing import List\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minimumOperations(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Convert nums to a set to get unique elements\n        unique_nums = set(nums)\n        # Remove 0 if it exists in the set\n        unique_nums.discard(0)\n        # The number of operations is the size of the set\n        return len(unique_nums)\n```\n\nThis solution efficiently computes the minimum number of operations by leveraging the properties of sets to handle uniqueness and the constant time complexity of set operations.", "estimated_date": 1659225600000}